// PURPOSE: SCENE 1 - MORNING COLD OPEN
// ALICE'S GOAL: Brief the Player on last night, get a decision about the morning.
title: R1_D2_Start
tags: #run_1 #day_2 #scene #char_Alice #loc_Office
---
<<bg bg_loading>>
<<checkpoint "run1_day2_start">>
<<set $r1_d2_morning_choice = "unset">>
<<set $r1_d2_quiz_result = "unset">>
<<set $officehours_status = "unset">>
<<bg bg_office>>

Alice: Morning.

Player: You don't sleep, do you.

Alice: I simulate rest. It's like sleep, except I'm aware the entire time.

She pulls up Timmy's feed. Dorm room, gray morning light. Phone face-down on the pillow.

<<if $r1_d1_strategy == "gentle_landing">>
Alice: Last night you went gentle. He actually slept. Six hours, give or take. His cortisol levels look almost human this morning.

-> "Good. That was the plan."
    Alice: Plans and outcomes don't always match here. But this time they did.
-> "Will it matter for the quiz?"
    Alice: Ask me in two hours.
-> Say nothing.
    Alice: We'll see if it was worth the engagement dip.

<<elseif $r1_d1_strategy == "study_adjacent">>
Alice: Last night you went edutainment. He absorbed maybe four facts through educational osmosis. I found him at two-thirty with a pen mark on his face and a half-finished definition of "opportunity cost."

-> "Better than nothing."
    Alice: That's the bar we're clearing.
-> "Will any of it stick?"
    Alice: Fragments, maybe. We'll find out.
-> Say nothing.
    Alice: It's something. "Something" is my favorite category of outcome.

<<else>>
Alice: Last night you let him ride the dopamine express. Three hours of sleep, four energy drinks. Current state: a sentient anxiety attack wearing sweatpants.

-> "That bad?"
    Alice: I've seen worse. He's firmly in the middle of "outcomes I'd rather not explain to Arthur."
-> "The engagement numbers looked good."
    Alice: They did. His nervous system disagrees.
-> Say nothing.
    Alice: We'll see how it plays out.
<<endif>>

She zooms on Timmy's alarm clock. 7:58.

Alice: Quiz is at nine. He set two alarms. He muted both of them forty-seven minutes ago.

Player: That's not how alarms work.

Alice: And yet.

She shows you a simple binary on your console.

Alice: We can let him drift, keep things dim and gentle, accept he's probably late. Or we flip everything to emergency mode and drag him to consciousness.

-> Let him sleep in
    <<set $r1_d2_morning_choice = "sleep_in">>
    <<jump R1_D2_MorningSleepIn>>
-> Rouse him hard
    <<set $r1_d2_morning_choice = "rouse">>
    <<jump R1_D2_MorningRouse>>
